<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'BROTHER'S KEEPER' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Peter Rainer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Documentary makers Joe Berlinger and Bruce Sinofksy provide a straightforward 
narrative on their highly publicized subject, which is a trial in upstate New 
York, where a dairy farmer was charged with murdering his own brother in the 
bed they shared. Was the ailing Bill Ward's death a mercy killing, or a case of 
sex gone bad? Or, as many in Munnsville (pop. 499) believed, was his brother 
Delbert innocent altogether? The movie isn't about the luridness of the 
situation so much as it is about the community of caring that grew up around 
Delbert and his other brothers (including Lyman Ward, pictured), who heretofore 
had been regarded as filthy, uneducated and possibly simple-minded outcasts 
(KCET Monday at 9 p.m.). Peter Rainer 
</P>
</TEXT>
