<HEADLINE>
<P>
RERUNS TO REWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Relive how The Mary Tyler Moore Show (Sunday at 10 p.m. on Nickelodeon) 
started when Nick at Nite airs the very first episode. 
</P>
<P>
 Fonzie falls in love with the sexy motorcycle queen Pinky Tuscadero (Roz 
Kelly) on a three-part Happy Days (Monday-Wednesday at 6:05 a.m. on TBS). 
</P>
<P>
 Robert Culp and Valerie Harper guest star on Columbo (Monday at 12:30 p.m. on 
A&E) in a thriller in which the detective investigates the murder of a pro 
football team owner. 
</P>
<P>
 TBS repeats the pilot episode of the long-running ABC comedy series Growing 
Pains (Monday at 3:35 p.m. on TBS). 
</P>
<P>
 Marty Ingels guest stars on The Dick Van Dyke Show (Monday at 11 p.m. on 
Nickelodeon). 
</P>
<P>
 Darren McGavin and George Maharis are featured in the 1973 "Cop Killer" 
episode of Shaft (Tuesday at 12:30 a.m. on TNT); Richard Roundtree stars. 
</P>
<P>
 The great Nancy Walker makes her first appearance as Rhoda's meddling mom on 
The Mary Tyler Moore Show (Tuesday at 10:30 p.m. on Nickelodeon). 
</P>
<P>
 Ed Asner plays a 30-year-old veteran who risks his life on the day of his 
retirement on Police Story (Wednesday at 3 p.m. on A&E). 
</P>
<P>
 Georgia Engel of "The Mary Tyler Moore Show" plays a meter maid who falls in 
love with Exidor on a two-part Mork & Mindy (Tuesday and Wednesday at 8:30 p.m. 
on Nickelodeon). 
</P>
<P>
 A young Meredith Baxter appears on The Partridge Family (Thursday at 8 p.m. on 
Nickelodeon) in an episode in which Chris and Tracy run away. 
</P>
<P>
 Tom Poston guest stars as Bob's friend, a.k.a. the Peeper, who returns to 
Chicago for a visit on The Bob Newhart Show (Thursday at 9:30 p.m. on 
Nickelodeon). 
</P>
<P>
 Dick Van Dyke's sons, Barry (now appearing with his dad on "Diagnosis Murder") 
and Christian, are featured on The Dick Van Dyke Show (Friday at 11 p.m. on 
Nickelodeon). 
</P>
<P>
 Very Very Nick at Nite (Saturday at 10 p.m. on Nickelodeon) presents "Very 
Very Derby" -- episodes of "The Partridge Family," "The Lucy Show," "Alfred 
Hitchcock Presents" and "Superman" that deal with racehorses. 
</P>
