<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSPECTIVES ON TELEPHONE MONITORING; PRIVACY IS VERY DIFFERENT IN THE 
ELECTRONIC AGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN M. DERSHOWITZ, Alan M. Dershowitz teaches at Harvard Law School and 
writes a syndicated column. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the post-Watergate era of omnipresent speakerphones, tape recorders and 
other electronic doodads, it is difficult to imagine anyone being surprised to 
learn that a big-city mayor takes precautions to assure that he is quoted 
accurately and that he has a record of what others have said to him.  
</P>
<P>
 It is almost certain that many politicians, executives and other public 
figures monitor their calls in one way or another.Now that the word is out, 
anyone who calls such people should be on notice that they do not have the 
usual deniability that has long been assumed to exist for informal telephone 
discussions. The current rules of the game are: Don't say it if you don't mean 
it, don't promise it if you can't deliver it and figure out some way of 
monitoring your side of the conversation.  
</P>
<P>
 Nor is the phone the only means of communication that has lost its status as 
confidential. Electronic mail, faxes, computer modems and face-to-face 
conversation all are subject to easy surveillance. And the courts have been of 
little help. The only means of communication that seem to have retained their 
sanctity are the religious confessional (certainly not the psychological 
consultation, witness the Menendez case) and the handwritten, sealed letter.  
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps the time has come for all of us to dig our fountain pens and our old 
stationery out of storage and start writing more letters to each other. The 
most confidential means of communication may be the most old-fashioned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
