<P>
9.1% OF U.S. LIVES IN HIGH-POLLUTION AREAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Almost 23 million Americans live in places that don't meet federal standards 
for pollutants like soot and acid aerosols, the stuff that produces that haze 
in the air, the American Lung Assn. said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Those people -- 9.1% of the population in 16 counties across the country, 
including Los Angeles and Denver -- are at risk for respiratory diseases and 
other health problems from the pollutants, the association said. 
</P>
