<HEADLINE>
<P>
WILLIAM WHITE; WON PULITZER FOR BIOGRAPHY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 William S. White, World War II correspondent, political reporter, columnist 
and Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer, died of a stroke Saturday.He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
 He covered Washington and World War II for the Associated Press, then joined 
the New York Times in 1945. He was the Times' chief congressional correspondent 
in 1958 when he left to write a syndicated column that appeared in 175 
newspapers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Taft Story," his biography of Robert A. Taft, the Republican senator from 
Ohio who ran for President in 1952, won the Pulitzer Prize in 1955. 
</P>
</TEXT>
