<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH: SOUTH-CENTRAL; BANK PRAISED FOR OPENING AREA OFFICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Community leaders last week heralded the opening of a Coast Federal Bank home 
loan office in the historic Dunbar Hotel, noting that it is the first major 
lending institution to locate in the area in years. 
</P>
<P>
 "The key thing here is that Coast Federal Bank has made a commitment to come 
into the area, and we have a community here with dire banking needs," said 
Anthony Scott, executive director of the Dunbar Economic Development Corp., 
which helped coordinate the move. "This is the first major bank to come and 
build on Central Avenue in decades." 
</P>
<P>
 The small, unassuming office at 4223 S. Central Ave. will begin taking 
applications this week. It will provide home loans for moderate- to low-income 
residents in South-Central, where the average home price is about $100,000. 
Bank officials said one lender's program will allow buyers to purchase a home 
with just a 5% down payment. 
</P>
<P>
 At the grand opening, community leaders and city officials said they hoped the 
loan office will help pave the way for other banks to come into South-Central. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think a lot of people will be watching to see what happens with this 
branch," said Paul Hudson, president of Broadway Federal Savings & Loan Assn., 
a South-Central bank. "If Coast does well here, it'll do away with the idea 
that you can't make money in South-Central." 
</P>
<P>
 Misperceptions and concern over default rates have long kept lenders at bay, 
Hudson said, because some lending institutions believe they are taking a higher 
risk on loans in areas such as South-Central. 
</P>
<P>
 "All those stereotypes are inaccurate and have led to people saying, 'Let's 
stay out,' " Hudson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Rob Hunt, president of Coast Federal Bank, agreed, adding that lenders suffer 
greater losses in more affluent areas where homes are more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
 "The type of loans made in these areas tend to perform better, and the default 
rates are much lower. It's nowhere near what it is in affluent areas," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 For now, bank officials and community leaders said, they will focus on getting 
the message out and inviting residents to stop by the office. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to make it here, and we'll do anything we can. And part of doing that 
will be getting out there into the community," Hudson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Information: (213) 233-1580. SANDRA HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
