<HEADLINE>
<P>
POPE EXPECTED TO RECOVER FULLY FROM BROKEN LEG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Pleased with the initial stages of Pope John Paul II's recovery from an 
operation to repair a broken thighbone, doctors said Saturday that he should be 
able to resume a normal life. 
</P>
<P>
 The 73-year-old Pope was resting comfortably without pain, fever or 
complications, papal spokesman Joaquin Navarro told reporters at a Vatican 
briefing. 
</P>
<P>
 "I found him in good spirits, very positive," Navarro said. 
</P>
<P>
 He said the Pope hoped to record his traditional Sunday noontime message for 
transmission to pilgrims in St. Peter's Square today. 
</P>
<P>
 Emilio Tresalti, director of Gemelli Hospital, where surgeons replaced a piece 
of the femur from John Paul's right leg with a metal prosthesis, said the Pope 
passed a tranquil first night with excellent prospects for a full recovery. 
</P>
<P>
 The pontiff will remain at the big Catholic hospital for two or three weeks, 
doctors say. He will need extensive therapy after that and will walk with a 
cane for a time, but should not have a limp once recovery is complete, his 
doctors said. 
</P>
<P>
 "There will be certain things like skiing that he will not be able to do, but 
the majority of people don't have any problems resuming a normal life after 
this procedure," Tresalti said. 
</P>
<P>
 John Paul was still groggy Saturday morning, but ate a light breakfast and 
planned later to concelebrate Mass with one of his secretaries, Navarro said. 
The Pope also chatted with Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican secretary of 
state, according to the papal spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
 In the Pope's absence, Sodano, effectively the Vatican's prime minister, is 
the senior official of the 950-million-member Roman Catholic Church, and 
Navarro said he will represent John Paul at upcoming meetings with visitors 
such as the president of Estonia and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. The 
accident forced cancellation of a weekend papal visit to Sicily and a scheduled 
trip to Belgium later this month. 
</P>
<P>
 The Vatican Curia will look after routine affairs of state, deferring 
important decisions until the Pope's return. As his recovery continues, John 
Paul will likely resume work in his hospital room. 
</P>
</TEXT>
